\f0\b\fs26 \ul Understanding the Menu
\f1\b0\fs24 \ulnone \

\f0\b \
\'93Protein sequence\'94 box:
\f1\b0  This is where you enter the sequence you want to search.\
\

\f0\b \'93UniProt ID\'94 box:
\f1\b0  If an AlphaFold prediction exists for your protein, you can enter the protein\'92s UniProt code here and the program will retrieve it and add its structure to the final alignment.\
\

\f0\b \'93Search PDB database?\'94 checkbox:
\f1\b0  If you don\'92t want the program to add PDB structures to the final alignment, you can uncheck this box. PDB search is enabled by default.\
\

\f0\b \'93% Identity threshold\'94 slider:
\f1\b0  You can adjust this slider to set the threshold for which species are included in the final result. Any species whose closest sequence has % identity lower than the threshold are excluded from the final alignment.\
\

\f0\b \'93Output file name\'94 box:
\f1\b0  If you want the output file to have a specific name, you can enter it here. If left empty, a generic name will be generated.
\f0\b \
\
\'93Update PDB database\'94 button:
\f1\b0  Click this button to update the local PDB sequence database. Updating the database is not necessary for the program to function, but it\'92s helpful to have the most recent structures on hand. Update as frequently as you see fit.\
\

\f0\b \'93Taxonomy Settings\'94 menu:
\f1\b0  This window allows you to handpick which species you want included in your search. All species in the database are organized by taxonomy, with checkboxes allowing you to enable or disable species or taxonomic groups. If you want to add a new species, see the database instructions document in the instructions folder.\
\
\

