\f0\b\fs26 \cf0 \ul Using the PyMOL output file
\f1\b0\fs24 \ulnone \
\
Along with each alignment, the program creates a file by the same name + \'91_pymol\'92 in the folder called \'93pymol output\'94. This is a PyMOL command file that will project the conservation scores from the corresponding alignment onto a 3D structure in PyMOL.\
\
To use the file, first open a PDB model of the protein in PyMOL. An AlphaFold structure prediction usually works best, but if a full-sequence solved structure exists, that should work as well. Just ensure that there are no unmodelled sections or extraneous tags, and that the sequence starts counting at 1. \
\
Then, in the command bar, type @, then drag the output file into the command bar. This should fill in the file path to the command file. Then press enter, and the commands will execute to colour the model. \
\
The darker the colour, the more conserved that residue is. White means completely unconserved, and the darkest blue means completely identical.\
